Well comrades, after multiple successful missions we finally made it back. Chief was super happy with us, and we were able to replace our bronze badges with nice, shiny silver ones! Once we get the gold badge then ask "why stop there?" once you get the gold badge you will have a marginally easier time making it to the end. So again, just focus on reaching the gold badge for right now and look at it as the final goal, since like I said once we reach it you'll have a much harder time convincing yourself to fail.

That's all the motivation & advice I've got for you today. Tomorrow we've got many more dangerous missions to go on, get a good nights rest soldiers. Capt. Hector's Log book. November 15th, 1887:

Yes. Yes, this is what the rumours meant. A hunter frozen in the ice, hands contorted to claws, mouth agape. With her left hand, she had plucked her own eye from the socket. It lies very close to the surface of the ice.

If the stories were true, there's a dark virtue in that eye. Take it, then. "Perhaps we should put it in a jar" I nodded... Do we have a jar?

We headed back along the shoreline, the crew laughing and bantering. I spotted something barely within my field of view. I crept towards it, not expecting anything to be here. The crew noticed my detour from the path and walked with me. Once we got closer the object in question revealed to be a ragged tent flapped in the freezing wind. Ice-encrusted bones lie tumbled at the flap. Someone came here to be forgotten.

"Let's gather what we can and get back, cap" I agreed and all of us got to work looting the place. After five minutes all that we got were an artefact, a mirrorcatch box, some leftover supplies, and a skull without its eye sockets. Perhaps the Alarming Scholar back home can verify if it's a real skull or not.

"Captain, look!" A crewman pointed towards the sky, a vibrant green flare illuminated the normally lightless sky. The signal of safety. "Let's hurry back" All of us ran back, hurry to get out of this place.

I prayed to Salt, Storm, and Stone that I will survive this voyage, for the deep dark zee is unforgiving.
